Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pour the @water{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.

Stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150%g} and @salt{¼%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, zest and cut the @lime{1}(zested and cut into wedges). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a #large bowl{}, combine the garlic, lime zest, @Breadcrumbs{10%g}, @salt{¼%tsp} and @water{2%tbsp} for the breadcrumbs, then add the @British Beef Mince{240%g}. Season with @ground black pepper{} and mix together with your hands.

Roll into evenly-sized balls, 5 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the meatballs onto a #large baking tray{}.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The meatballs are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, trim the @Green Beans{80%g}, then cut into thirds. Trim the @Carrot{1}(trimmed), then slice into 1/2cm thick rounds (no need to peel).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the green beans and carrot. Stir-fry until tender, ~{6-7%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Lower the heat, then add the @Yellow Thai Style Paste{45%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @Peanut Butter{30%g} to the pan. Cook for ~{30%seconds}, stirring vigorously.

> TIP: If your peanut butter has hardened, put the sachet in a bowl of hot water for 1 min to loosen.

Stir in the @Coconut Milk{180%ml}, @Soy Sauce{15%ml} and @Sugar{1%tsp} for the sauce until combined and bring to the boil. Simmer until thickened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

When the meatballs are cooked, add them to the satay sauce and simmer, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from the heat and squeeze in some lime juice.

Taste and season with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and more lime juice if needed.

When everything's ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then share between your bowls.

Top with the beef meatball satay curry.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side for squeezing over. Enjoy!